= Introduction to Species Interactions

Species interactions are fundamental to ecology, influencing population dynamics, community structure, and evolution. All organisms participate in consumer-resource relationships, forming the basis of food chains and ecosystems.

== Types of Species Interactions

Interactions are classified by effects on each species: benefit (+), harm (-), or neutral (0). Main types include:

- Consumer-resource interactions (+/-): Predators benefit, prey suffer
- Competition (-/-): Both species harmed by resource sharing
- Mutualism (+/+): Both species benefit
- Commensalism (+/0): One benefits, other unaffected
- Amensalism (-/0): One harmed, other unaffected

